830. Anaxagorae: b. at Clazomenae, about 5⁰⁰ nc. Anax· agoras taught that there is an indefinite number oi primitive sub stances, qualitatively different, corresponding to all the various kinds of matter. Thus, fiesh is made up ot minute particles oi fiesh, bone oi particles ot bone, gold ol gold, and so forth These particle· are underived and indestructible. They are not, however, atoms, tor they are infinitely divisible. The four elemeuts he thought to be merely a mixture oi all kinds oi primitive particles; their “apparent simple· nese he explains by saying that, on account ot the amalgamation ot all possible determinate substances, not one ol these is perceived in its distinctive individuality, but only that is perceived in which they ali agree.” To explain the union of these in living bodies. and the creation and ongoing oi the universe, Anaxagoras taught the exist· enee oi a Νοῦς, an incorporenl, intelligent Force, acting upon matter from without. He was the first who grasped at the idea of essential difference between matter and spirit; at the conception also of an intelligent Final Canse.
